    {
      "id": "https://boingboing.net/2026/03/16/memory-hack-self-testing-beats-re-reading-by-50-research-shows.html",
      "url": "https://boingboing.net/2026/03/16/memory-hack-self-testing-beats-re-reading-by-50-research-shows.html",
      "title": "[Boing Boing] Memory hack: self-testing beats re-reading by 50%, research shows",
      "content_html": "<img src=\"https://i0.wp.com/boingboing.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/braind.jpg?fit=1200%2C800&quality=60&ssl=1\" style=\"width:100%;max-height:300px;object-fit:cover;\" />\n<a href=\"https://boingboing.net/2026/03/16/memory-hack-self-testing-beats-re-reading-by-50-research-shows.html\" rel=\"nofollow\" title=\"Memory hack: self-testing beats re-reading by 50%, research shows\"><img alt=\"ahmetmapush/shutterstock.com\" class=\"webfeedsFeaturedVisual wp-post-image\" height=\"800\" src=\"https://i0.wp.com/boingboing.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/braind.jpg?fit=1200%2C800&amp;quality=60&amp;ssl=1\" style=\"display: block; margin: auto; margin-bottom: 5px;\" width=\"1200\" /></a><p>Students who test themselves on new material remember about 50% more than students who just re-read their notes. That's the core finding from decades of retrieval practice research — and it runs counter to how most people actually study.</p>\n<p>The typical study session involves reading, highlighting, and reading again. &#8212; <a class=\"read-more\" href=\"https://boingboing.net/2026/03/16/memory-hack-self-testing-beats-re-reading-by-50-research-shows.html\">Read the rest </a></p>\n<p>The post <a href=\"https://boingboing.net/2026/03/16/memory-hack-self-testing-beats-re-reading-by-50-research-shows.html\">Memory hack: self-testing beats re-reading by 50%, research shows</a> appeared first on <a href=\"https://boingboing.net\">Boing Boing</a>.</p>",
      "date_published": "2026-03-16T18:41:42+00:00",
      "authors": [
